## 3. Authentication — How It Works

This is the most important thing to understand before you start.

### How login works:
1. User submits email and password
2. Backend returns an **access token** in the response body
3. Backend also sets a **refresh token** in an **httpOnly cookie** automatically — you cannot read or touch this cookie from JavaScript, the browser handles it
4. You save the access token in memory or localStorage
5. Every API request must include the access token in the `Authorization` header

### How token refresh works:
- The access token expires after a short time (e.g. 15 minutes)
- When it expires, the API returns a `401` status
- When you get a `401`, call `POST /auth/refresh` — the browser automatically sends the cookie
- The server returns a new access token
- Retry the original request with the new token
- If refresh also fails → redirect user to login page

### What to store in localStorage after login:
```javascript
localStorage.setItem("token", data.data.accessToken);
localStorage.setItem("role", data.data.role);       // "STUDENT", "ADMIN", or "LECTURER"
localStorage.setItem("userId", data.data.id);
```

